  <section>
    <div class="block">
      <p>
        <span class="first-character greenish">Y</span>
        our first ski or snowboard lesson is such an exciting experience - you’re finally hitting the slopes and starting a winter sport! 
        Sure, it might feel a little awkward at first (everyone has their share of wobbly moments), but that’s all part of the learning process. 
        The key is being prepared, so you feel more confident and ready to enjoy your first day on snow. As a newbie to skiing or snowboarding, 
        knowing what to expect can make your first lesson way less stressful, a lot more fun, and a better learning experience.
      </p>
      <h2 class="inline-title margin-top-20">Arriving at the Resort </h2>
      <p class="margin-top-10">
        Getting to the ski resort is part of the adventure, but <a href="https://snocountry.com/mountain-life/travel/winter-driving-safety-tips/" target="_blank">winter travel</a> can throw some curveballs. 
        Snowy or icy roads might slow you down, so make sure to leave extra time for the drive. Once you’re at the resort, the parking lot can be busy, but don’t stress—you’ve got this. 
        Arriving early will help you feel more relaxed and ready for your lesson.      
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>
  <section>
    <div class="block">
      <img class="section-image" src="/assets/images/mountain-life/beginner-guide/ski-school.jpg" alt="The A-frame snowsports ski school building at Wachusett Mountain Massachusetts" />
